# Dashboard & Report UX Standards

When any skill generates Salesforce dashboards or reports, apply these constraints.

## Dashboard Component Sizing

- Each component must occupy **at most 9 tiles** (e.g. 3×3, 3×2, 2×3). Never exceed 9 tiles per component.
- Use tile size to communicate importance: KPI metrics → 1–2 tiles, trend charts → 4–6 tiles, summary tables → up to 9 tiles.
- Set `<columnSize>` in dashboard XML to use Salesforce's standard sizing — do not inflate tile dimensions beyond the platform default. Never use values that force horizontal scrolling.
- Target **12 components or fewer** per dashboard so everything is visible without vertical scrolling on a standard 1080p display.
- Group related metrics into a single component (e.g. stacked bar) rather than spreading them across multiple oversized components.

## Readability

- Use short, descriptive component titles (≤40 characters).
- Default to chart types that communicate at a glance: donut, horizontal bar, metric (single-value), gauge. Avoid pivot tables and matrix reports as dashboard components.
- Apply meaningful sort order (descending by value, chronological) — never leave the default unsorted.
- Limit report groupings to **2 levels max** in dashboard source reports to keep visuals clean.
- Use conditional highlighting / color thresholds on metric components when a target value exists.

## Dashboard Component Text Standards

Every text slot on a dashboard component is visible to the audience. Empty, default, or placeholder text ("Untitled Component", "Sum of Amount", "Record Count") instantly looks unfinished. Fill every slot with intentional, audience-facing copy.

### Required text slots and how to write them

| Slot | XML element | What to write | Bad | Good |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Component title (`<title>`) | `<title>` | Plain English, audience-facing, ≤40 chars, no field API names | `Sum_of_npc__Amount__c` | `Total Gifts This Year` |
| Component header / subtitle | `<header>` | Optional context ("YTD as of today"), ≤60 chars | `Header` | `Year-to-date through this week` |
| Component footer | `<footer>` | Source / freshness note ("Refreshed daily 6 AM CT"), ≤60 chars | `(empty)` | `Refreshed daily • Excludes pledges` |
| Metric label (single-value) | `<metricLabel>` | Unit or qualifier shown next to the number, ≤20 chars | `Total` | `Donors • FY26` |
| Axis title — X | `<chartAxisXLabel>` | Plain English label for the dimension, ≤24 chars | `CALENDAR_MONTH` | `Month` |
| Axis title — Y | `<chartAxisYLabel>` | Plain English measure with unit, ≤24 chars | `SUM:Amount` | `Gifts ($)` |
| Legend labels | source report column labels | Plain English, ≤20 chars per series | `npc__Status__c` | `Status` |
| Group-by label in summary report | report `<groupingLevel>` `<header>` overrides | Plain English with case ("By Program") | `program__c` | `By Program` |
| Tooltip / data-label units | report column custom labels | Always include the unit ($, %, count, hrs) when the number is ambiguous | `247000` | `$247,000` |
| Empty-state text | dashboard component `<chartTextNoDataMessage>` (where supported) | One-line guidance not a stack trace | `No records found.` | `No gifts yet for this period — check back after EOD batch.` |
| Filter labels (dynamic dashboard) | dashboard `<filter>` `<name>` | What the user picks, not the field | `npc__Region__c` | `Region` |

### Text-content rules

1. **No API names ever appear on screen.** Strip namespace prefixes (`npc__`, `npsp__`, `pmdm__`), trailing `__c`, and underscores. Convert to title case. If a field has no UI label, set one before using it on a dashboard.
2. **No SOQL function syntax on screen.** "Sum of Amount" is OK, "SUM(npc__Amount__c)" is not. Salesforce defaults to the latter — override with the report column custom label.
3. **Units belong in the title or the axis label, not both.** A bar chart titled "Gifts ($)" should not also have "$" in every data label. Pick one location and remove duplication.
4. **Date formats stay consistent across the dashboard.** Pick one (`Mon YYYY`, `Q1 FY26`, `2026-W17`) and use it on every component. Mixed date formats look like the dashboard was assembled by three different people.
5. **Match the audience's vocabulary.** Donors are not "Records". Volunteers are not "Users". Gifts are not "Opportunities" in an NPC org. Translate platform terms into the org's domain language in every visible label.
6. **Numbers ≥ 10,000 use thousands separators.** `$247,000` not `$247000`. Use the report column display format, not Apex `String.valueOf()`.
7. **Truncate gracefully.** If a label hits the slot's character limit, end with a complete word, not mid-syllable. Never let Salesforce auto-truncate with `…` on a public-facing dashboard.
8. **The dashboard has a title too.** Set `<dashboard><title>` and `<dashboard><description>` — these appear in the dashboard list view and in shared links.

### Report column setup that drives clean dashboard text

Even with perfect dashboard XML, dashboards inherit text from their source report's column setup. So in every report that powers a dashboard component:

- Set a **column custom label** for every grouping and aggregate column (e.g. group by `npc__Program__r.Name` with column label "Program"; aggregate `SUM(npc__Amount__c)` with label "Gifts ($)").
- Use **Display Units** on the report header (Show in Thousands / Millions) when amounts are ≥ 6 digits, so the dashboard shows `$247K` instead of `$247,000`.
- Set a **report description** (1 sentence, business voice) — it shows under the report title when a viewer drills in from the dashboard.

## Layout

- Arrange components in a logical reading order: KPI summary row at top, trend charts in the middle, detail tables (if any) at the bottom.
- Keep the dashboard to a **single viewport** — the end user should see every component without scrolling.
- If the data requires more than 12 components, split into multiple focused dashboards rather than one scrollable mega-dashboard.

## Report Source Best Practices

- Each dashboard component should reference a dedicated summary or matrix report scoped to the data it visualizes — no reusing one wide report for unrelated components.
- Filter reports to a reasonable default date range (current FY, last 12 months) so components render meaningful data immediately.

## Anti-Patterns — Never Do These

- ❌ Components that span 2+ columns forcing horizontal scroll
- ❌ Dashboards with 20+ components requiring vertical scroll
- ❌ Tabular (detail) reports as dashboard source — use summary/matrix
- ❌ Unfiltered reports pulling org-wide data into a dashboard component
- ❌ Truncated axis labels caused by oversized chart data in undersized tiles
- ❌ Component title that includes an API name, namespace prefix, or `__c` suffix
- ❌ Default Salesforce labels left untouched ("Sum of Amount", "Record Count", "Untitled Component", "CALENDAR_MONTH")
- ❌ A chart with a single bar / one wedge of a donut that takes 90%+ of the visual (the data shape problem — fix it by re-seeding distribution per `sf-nonprofit-demo-data` Report-Shaped Data Generation)
- ❌ Mixed date formats across components on the same dashboard
- ❌ Numbers shown without unit context ($, %, count, hrs) when the unit isn't obvious from the title
- ❌ Empty `<header>` / `<footer>` / `<description>` slots when a one-line audience-facing string would clarify the component
